        <name>38.2.2.1 Expected net profit</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In the manufacture of petroleum the distilling temperature (\(T^\circ\)C) is crucial in determining the quality of the final product.&amp;nbsp; \(T\) can be considered as a random variable uniformly distributed over \({@na@}^\circ\)C to \({@nb@}^\circ\)C.&amp;nbsp; It costs&amp;nbsp; &#163;\( A\) to produce 1 gallon of petroleum. If the oil distils at temperatures less than or equal to&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.9375rem;"&gt;\({@nm@}^\circ\)C the product sells for&amp;nbsp; &#163;\(B\) per gallon.&amp;nbsp; If it distils at a temperature greater than \({@nm@}^\circ\)C it sells for&amp;nbsp; &#163;\(D\) per gallon.&amp;nbsp; Find the formula for the expected net profit per gallon.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Expected net profit per gallon = [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]&amp;nbsp;[[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;The distribution for the distilling temperature is \(T \sim \text{Uniform}({@na@}, {@nb@})\). The probability the distilling temperature is less than or equal to \({@nm@}^\circ\)C is:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;\[ \text{P}(T\leq{@nm@}) = \dfrac{{@nm@} - {@na@}}{{@nb@} - {@na@}} = {@nr1@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;By the complement rule, the probability that the distilling temperature exceeds&amp;nbsp;\({@nm@}^\circ\)C is:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;\[\text{P}(T &amp;gt; {@nm@}) = 1 - \text{P}(T \leq {@nm@}) = 1 - {@nr1@} = {@1 - nr1@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.9375rem;"&gt;The net profit (sell price - cost price) per gallon under these two scenarios are presented in the table below:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;center&gt;&lt;table frame="void" rules="all" border="1"&gt;&lt;thead&gt;&lt;tr class="header"&gt;&lt;th style="text-align: center;"&gt;Scenario&lt;/th&gt;
&lt;th style="text-align: center;"&gt;\(T \leq {@nm@}\)&lt;br&gt;&lt;/th&gt;
&lt;th style="text-align: center;"&gt;\(T &amp;gt; {@nm@}\)&lt;/th&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/thead&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr class="odd"&gt;
&lt;td style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;span class="math inline"&gt;net profit&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style="text-align: center;"&gt;&#163;\((B-A)\)&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style="text-align: center;"&gt;&#163;\((D-A)\)&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr class="odd"&gt;
&lt;td style="text-align: center;"&gt;Probability&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style="text-align: center;"&gt;&amp;nbsp;\({@nr1@}\)&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td style="text-align: center;"&gt;\({@1-nr1@}\)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/center&gt;Therefore, the expected net profit per gallon is:&lt;br&gt;\[\text{E}(\text{net profit}) = {@nr1@}(B-A) + {@1-nr1@}(D-A) = &#163;{@ta@}. \]&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
